		<header>
			
			<h1>Discarding is a key challenge in fisheries policy reform</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 1 March 2011, the Fisheries Commissioner invited members of the European Parliament, EU fisheries ministers and the Court of Auditors for an informal political discussion on how to end discards in the context of the reform of the CFP. She reminded that: 'In 2004, the FAO estimated that 7.3 million tonnes, that is 8% of the total fish catches were discarded ... let me give you some figures for European fisheries, which proves that we are doing much worse than the global average: in the whitefish fishery up to half of the catch is thrown overboard and in the flatfish fishery we are even talking about 70% of the catches being discarded ... I consider discarding of fish unethical, a waste of natural resources and a waste of fishermen’s effort ... Therefore, I am considering proposing a discard ban as part of the CFP reform proposals.’</p><p>In preparation for this meeting, the NGO platform <i>Ocean 2012</i>&nbsp;published its position on discards, highlighting that ‘the CFP reform offers an excellent opportunity to establish new policies that will address the discard problem. It is vital that unwanted catches are avoided in the first place’. The platform advocates a discard ban: ‘All caught fish needs to be counted against quota’. Special attention should be given to how measures to counter by-catch can be ‘translated’ to apply to EU fleets fishing in the waters of third countries. As a priority, the emphasis should be on the need to promote selective fishing and to ban destructive fishing practices. This is particularly important in the coastal zone of tropical countries, where wasteful and destructive practices directly affect local coastal communities which depend on fishing for their livelihoods. In the case of the EU distant-water fleet, <i>Ocean2012</i>&nbsp;advocates that the use of the most selective fishing gears should be a pre-requisite condition for participation in fishing under FPAs. The EU should initiate the inclusion of the issue of discarding in the negotiations for FPAs. Third countries also need to be convinced of the necessity to introduce measures to stop the waste of their resources.</p><p>The Fisheries Commissioner sent a reply to this position, highlighting that she was committed to stopping discards undertaken by EU vessels in international waters or in waters of third countries ‘... as, indeed, we need to meet the same standards of sustainability and environmental protection for the EU fleet, irrespective of where it operates’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Speech by the Fisheries Commissioner at the high-level meeting on banning discards, <i>Discarding: Key challenges in Fisheries Policy Reform</i>, 1 March 2011<br />

<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/commission_2010-2014/damanaki/headlines/speeches/2011/03/20110301_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/commission_2010-2014/damanaki/headlines/speeches/201...</a><br />
<i>Ocean 2012’s </i>position on discards, December 2010<br />

<a href="http://www.ocean2012.eu/channel/view_resource/id/129676http://www.ocean2012.eu/channel/view_resource/id/129676" target="_self">http://www.ocean2012.eu/channel/view_resource/id/129676http://www.ocean2...</a><br />
The Fisheries Commissioner’s response, 15 February 2011<br />
<a href="http://www.cape-cffa.org/IMG/pdf/CAB19_0215114906_001.pdf" target="_self">http://www.cape-cffa.org/IMG/pdf/CAB19_0215114906_001.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In the context of the debate on the elimination of discards, it is important to note the willingness of the EU Commissioner to apply the same standards to EU vessels fishing in international waters as well as in third-country waters. In the case of EU fleets fishing in ACP waters, it could be worth considering whether some aspects of the fishing operations associated with discards, such as the use of unselective gear, should be phased out in favour of more selective and environmentally friendly fishing methods. One way to achieve this would be to give preferential access, through FPAs, to those operators using the best available practices and technologies.</p>
		</div>
		
